    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-07-02T06:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-07-02T06:44:00-05:00" n="442"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d442">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.20/349: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hall</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-07-02T11:00:00-00:44"
                            >July 2, 1930—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 2:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>92. George W. Lewis was commissioned yesterday afternoon<note n="34"
                        xml:id="d442fn34">He had arrived in Monrovia on June 14, 1936.</note> as
                    major in the Liberian frontier force. The President of Liberia is of the opinion
                    that Lewis is a mere military adviser who is outranked by two Liberian majors
                    and the Secretary of War here and gave instructions accordingly.</p>
                <p>While the Liberian Government will be interested in the views of Lewis, it is
                    believed that he will have little actual authority.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
